2 Neural Network Packages in R

R has several packages for dealing with NNs, like neuralnet, nnet or RSNNS.

Package neuralnet.
Description: Training of neural networks using backpropagation, resilient backpropagation with (Riedmiller, 1994) or without weight backtracking (Riedmiller and Braun, 1993) or the modified globally convergent version by Anastasiadis et al. (2005). The package allows flexible settings through custom-choice of error and activation function. Furthermore, the calculation of generalized weights (Intrator O & Intrator N, 1993) is implemented.
Reference manual: neuralnet.pdf

Package nnet.
Description: Software for feed-forward neural networks with a single hidden layer, and for multinomial log-linear models.
Reference manual: nnet.pdf

The methods implemented in the above packages are available in the caret package framework. caret uses nnet both for classification and regression, neuralnet only for regression.

Note that sigmoid activation function is only applied to the output of the hidden layer. This is because by default neuralnet() has argument linear.output=TRUE which means that output layer has no activation function. Change it to FALSE if application of sigmoid to output is necessary.

Function compute() computes the outputs of all neurons for specific arbitrary covariate vectors given a trained neural network (like predict()).

3.1.1 Comparison with logistic regression

The fitted neural network implements the formulas:

Î·=Î²0,2+Î²1,2(Î²0,1+Î²1,1x1+Î²2,1,x2)Î·=Î²0,2+Î²1,2(Î²0,1+Î²1,1x1+Î²2,1,x2)
=(Î²0,2+Î²1,2Î²0,1)+(Î²1,2Î²1,1)x1+(Î²1,2Î²2,1,)x2=(Î²0,2+Î²1,2Î²0,1)+(Î²1,2Î²1,1)x1+(Î²1,2Î²2,1,)x2
=B0+B1x1+B2x2,=B0+B1x1+B2x2,
 where

Î²0,2=Î²0,2= -0.1034244
Î²1,2=Î²1,2= 1.1209354
Î²0,1=Î²0,1= -2.236057
Î²1,1=Î²1,1= 5.9314313
Î²2,1=Î²2,1= 5.9692212

and

B0=Î²0,2+Î²1,2Î²0,1=B0=Î²0,2+Î²1,2Î²0,1= -0.1034244 ++ 1.1209354 ÃÃ -2.236057 == -2.6098998

B1=Î²1,2Î²1,1=B1=Î²1,2Î²1,1= 1.1209354 ÃÃ 5.9314313 == 6.6487511

B2=Î²1,2Î²2,1,=B2=Î²1,2Î²2,1,= 1.1209354 ÃÃ 5.9692212 == 6.6911112

That is: linear predictor Î·Î· is estimated as Î·=B0+B1x1+B2x2Î·=B0+B1x1+B2x2.
The output of the network yy goes through activation function (axon hillock) of the form of inverse logit function g(u)=11+eâug(u)=11+eâu, i.e

11+exp(âÎ·)=eÎ·1+eÎ·.11+exp(âÎ·)=eÎ·1+eÎ·.

But this is formula for probability of logistic regression!

This means that neural network with one perceptron and default configuration with no hidden layers with inverse logit activation function must be equivalent to logistic regression

ln(p1âp)=B0+B1x1+B2x2.lnâ¡(p1âp)=B0+B1x1+B2x2.

For comparison with logistic regression calculate predictions given by perceptron:

  1. Coefficients.
B_0<-nnDa$weights[[1]][[2]][1]+nnDa$weights[[1]][[2]][2]*nnDa$weights[[1]][[1]][1]
B_1<-nnDa$weights[[1]][[2]][2]*nnDa$weights[[1]][[1]][2]
B_2<-nnDa$weights[[1]][[2]][2]*nnDa$weights[[1]][[1]][3]
  1. Linear predictor.
manPred<-B_0+B_1*da$x1+B_2*da$x2
  1. Probabilities of success.
predNeuron<-nnDa$act.fct(manPred)

Probabilities estimated by logistic regression:

Logistic<-glm(y~x1+x2,data=da,family=binomial)
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
LogisticCoeff<-Logistic$coefficients

Compare coefficients.

cbind(Logistic=LogisticCoeff,Neuron=c(B_0,B_1,B_2))
##             Logistic    Neuron
## (Intercept) -23.3595 -2.609900
## x1           46.7190  6.648751
## x2           46.7190  6.691111

Coefficients do not look the same.
But check predicted probabilities.

PredLogistic<-predict(Logistic,type="response")
cbind(Neuron=predNeuron,Logistic=PredLogistic)
##      Neuron     Logistic
## 1 0.0685040 7.163054e-11
## 2 0.9833934 1.000000e+00
## 3 0.9826873 1.000000e+00
## 4 0.9999781 1.000000e+00

Note that neural network fits with 5 parameters while logistic regression fits with 3 parameters.

3.1.2 Remove unnecessary parameters and force perceptron to fit more accurately

In order to better reproduce the results of logistic regression do the following:

  • Remove unnecessary weights from perceptron: remove from fitting exclude=c(4,5) and replace them with fixed values constant.weights=c(0.1)
  • Increase number of repetitions to 10. Number of repetitions is the number of training processes which start from random initial values in order to avoid local minima
  • reduce threshold, a numeric value specifying the threshold for the partial derivatives of the error function as stopping criteria
set.seed(14)
nnDa <- neuralnet(y~x1+x2,data=da, err.fct="sse",rep=10, exclude=c(4,5),
                  constant.weights = c(0,1),threshold=1e-20)
plot(nnDa,rep="best")

Compare the coefficients with fitted logistic regression

LogisticCoeff
## (Intercept)          x1          x2 
##    -23.3595     46.7190     46.7190

Parameter hidden is a vector specifying the number of hidden layers and hidden neurons in each layer. For example vector c(4,2) indicates a neural network with two hidden layers, the first layer consists of 4 neurons, the second consists of 2 neurons.

Parameter err.fct is a differentiable error function. Strings âsseâ or âceâ that are possible values refer to âsum of squared errorsâ (regression) and âcross entropyâ (classification). Default: âsseâ.

If necessary print summary (long output not shown).

print(nnHit)

The trained neural network can be plotted by

plot(nnHit, rep="best")

where rep is the number of repetition of the neural network.
If rep=âbestâ, the repetition with the smallest error will be plotted.
If rep is not specified all repetitions are plotted, each in a separate terminal window.
The plot displays the structure of the trained neural network. It includes by default the trained weights, all intercepts (blue) as well as basic information about the training process like the overall error and the number of steps needed to converge.

The list nnHit$result.matrix contains main results of the neural network.

Neural network is more accurate, but has many more parameters. The total number of parameters including all weights and intercepts is

sum(sapply(nnHit$weights[[1]],length))
## [1] 29

Now include all variables in the model. Two important changes should be done in this case.

  • Unfortunately neuralnet() does not understand the notation Salary~.. The predictors need to be listed directly.
  • Some columns of the data set are factors. Since neuralnet() can handle only numeric variables, convert factors to numeric format with data.matrix().
hitFormula = paste("Salary", paste(names(Hitters)[-match("Salary", names(Hitters))],
                                         collapse = '+'),sep="~")
hitFormula
## [1] "Salary~AtBat+Hits+HmRun+Runs+RBI+Walks+Years+CAtBat+CHits+CHmRun+CRuns+CRBI+CWalks+League+Division+PutOuts+Assists+Errors+NewLeague"

Train the model with the same hidden layer as above.

set.seed(0)
nnHit <- neuralnet(hitFormula,data=data.matrix(Hitters), 
                    hidden=7, err.fct="sse")
cat('MSE = ',sum((nnHit$net.result[[1]]-Hitters$Salary)^2)/nrow(Hitters),'\n')
## MSE =  0.3764201

Note that increasing the number of predictors did not improve result. The reason is that minimizing the function of many variables on non-convex set the algorithm stops at a local minimum and does not reach the global one.

Train model with two hidden layers, 5 neurons in the first level and 4 in the second level.
Set seed to 11.

3.4 Example. Galtonâs data

Galtonâs data on the heights of parents and their children can be found in the package HistData. This data set lists the individual observations for 934 children in 205 families on which Galton (1886) based his cross-tabulation.

library(HistData)
data(GaltonFamilies)

Families are largely listed in descending order of fathers and mothers height. Shuffle them to ensure correct cross validation procedure further on.

set.seed(0)
data = GaltonFamilies[sample(nrow(GaltonFamilies)),
                   -which(names(GaltonFamilies) %in% c("family","midparentHeight"))]
data$gender = as.integer(data$gender)
kable(head(data,5))
father mother children childNum gender childHeight
398 70.0 61.0 2 2 2 67.0
836 66.5 62.5 7 5 1 62.5
679 68.5 63.5 1 1 2 68.2
129 71.0 69.0 5 2 2 74.0
930 62.0 66.0 3 1 2 64.0

We removed family number and midparentHeight, which is actually linear combination of parentsâ height: midparentHeight = (father + 1.08*mother)/2.
Character variable gender was transformed to numeric.

Convergence of neural networks is usually faster if the input variables are normalized to have zero mean and unit variance (see, for example, Efficient BackProp).
One exception to scaling all covariances to the same average and variance occurs when it is known that some inputs are of less significance than others. In such a case, it can be beneficial to scale the less significant inputs down so that they are âless visibleâ to the learning process.

Scaling of data for neural networks is often different from traditional z-scoring. Because output of perceptron is filtered by a sigmoid activation function it will be scaled between zero and one. This makes centering each variable at minimum and scaling it by range (max-min) more convenient.

mins<-apply(data,2,min)
maxs<-apply(data,2,max)
scaledData = data.frame(scale(data, center = mins, scale = maxs - mins))

3.4.1 Predicting childâs height by neural network with conventional design

Now perform neural network training using caret.
Load the package and partition data set into train and test subsets.

library(caret)
set.seed(0)
inTraining <- createDataPartition(data[,1], p = .8, list = FALSE)
train <- scaledData[ inTraining,]
test  <- scaledData[-inTraining,]
formulaG = formula(childHeight ~ father+mother+children+childNum+gender)

Train neural network with one hidden layer using 3-fold cross validation.
Select number of neurons in single hidden layer by grid search between 3 and 7.
Recall that the rule of thumb size of hidden layer is defined as average between sizes of input and output layers: 5+12=35+12=3.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 3, returnResamp = "final")
tStart<-proc.time()
set.seed(0)
nnGTrain <- train(formulaG, data = train, method = "neuralnet", 
                  trControl = ctrl, 
                  tuneGrid = data.frame(layer1 = 3:7, layer2 = 0, layer3 = 0),
                  stepmax = 1e5)
tEnd<-proc.time()
(TimeSpent_1<-tEnd-tStart)
##    user  system elapsed 
##   18.41    0.04   18.64

Print summary and plot the final network

print(nnGTrain)

Compare results with linear regression.

lmFit <- lm(formulaG, data = train)
pr.lm.train<-lmFit$fitted.values
pr.lm.test<-predict(lmFit,test)
pr.nn.train<-predict(nnGTrain,train)
pr.nn.test<-predict(nnGTrain,test)
compare <- data.frame(lm_MSE=c(mean(lmFit$residuals^2),
                              mean((pr.lm.test-test$childHeight)^2)),
                     nn_MSE=c(mean((pr.nn.train-train$childHeight)^2),
                              mean((pr.nn.test-test$childHeight)^2)) ) 
rownames(compare) <- c('train','test')
print(compare)

To calculate predictions from the trained network in the original format unscale the predictions obtained by compute()

pr.nn.test <- pr.nn.test*(max(train$childHeight)-min(train$childHeight))+min(train$childHeight)

Plot predictions against the actual response values.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

3.4.2 Simplify the network

Recall that logistic regression classification accuracy of these data, calculated in the lecture on decision trees was 0.881.

Though Data$gender is a factor with two levels, neuralnet() cannot accept it as response and gives diagnostics
âerr.fct was automatically set to sum of squared error (sse), because the response is not binaryâ.

Create binary proxy for gender.

Data$male <- Data$gender=="male"

Scale input variables

Data$scaledMidParHeight <- scale(Data$midparentHeight,center=min(Data$midparentHeight),
                                 scale=diff(range(Data$midparentHeight)))
Data$scaledChildHeight = scale(Data$childHeight,center=min(Data$childHeight),
                               scale=diff(range(Data$childHeight)))

Partition data into train (2323) and test (1313) sets.

set.seed(17)
testInd <- sample(nrow(Data), trunc(nrow(Data)/3))
train <- Data[-testInd,]
test <- Data[testInd,]

Fit the model with 7 neurons in one hidden layer to the train set. The error function to be chosen in this case is cross entropy err.fct="ce".

set.seed(0)
nnFit <- neuralnet(male~scaledMidParHeight+scaledChildHeight,                    
                   data = train, err.fct = "ce",
                   hidden = 7, threshold = 0.01,
                   linear.output=FALSE)
plot(nnFit,rep="best")

Predict classes using the test set. Use method compute() for prediction. It computes the outputs of all neurons for specific arbitrary covariate vectors given a trained neural network.

Remember to make the order of the covariates the same in the new matrix or data frame as in the original neural network.

Note that in spite of using formula in neuralnet() call we cannot put, for example, train or test data frames as arguments.
We have to remove unused columns from these data frames.

predict <- (compute(nnFit,test[c("scaledMidParHeight",
                                "scaledChildHeight")])$net.result > 0.5)*1

4.2 Example. Rectangular class domain

Simulate the data with another shape of classes. Each observation is three-dimensional vector with two numeric features and one categorical (type) with possible values âPositiveâ or âNegativeâ. The problem is to identify type on the basis of first two features.

N = 1000
xPos = 0.2
yMinPos = 0.2
yMaxPos = 0.7
set.seed(0)
newData = data.frame(y=runif(N),x=runif(N))
newData$type = with(newData,x>xPos & y>yMinPos & y<yMaxPos)
n = N/10
newData$type[1:n] = c(TRUE,FALSE)[1+rbinom(n, 1, 0.5)]

We also used Multiclass logloss for estimating prediction quality of previous methods. Calculate it for fitted network.

MultiLogLoss <- function(act, pred)
{
  eps = 1e-15;
  pred[pred<eps] = eps      
  pred[pred> (1-eps)] = 1-eps
  #normalize rows
  ll = sum(act*log(sweep(pred, 1, rowSums(pred), FUN="/")))
  ll = -ll/nrow(act)
  return(ll);
}

actMatrix = model.matrix(~-1+testY)
print(MultiLogLoss(actMatrix,
                   predict(nnFitOtto,testX,type='prob')))
## [1] 0.3381823

Worse than SVM, but, as was noted in the lecture on SVM, all these methods have many parameters to be tuned in order to improve the results.
